ICS School Android Application Mock-Up Business Case

1.0 Introduction/ Background (Saloni)
J-Unit is a group created in Informatics 151 at the University of California, Irvine. J-Unit is committed to the ideas of improvement in different aspects of UCI’s campus. As all members are continuously involved students within the Donald Bren School of ICS, J-Unit believes that there should be an easier way to view important ICS-related information on a mobile device. In efforts to balance extracurricular activities, classes, and a social life, students nowadays are becoming increasingly dependent on smartphones and mobile apps. These applications allow them to keep up with their “on the go” lifestyle and aid students in accessing important information they need when they are unable to be on their laptops and computers. Already, the development of the UCI Mobile App have provided students with an easier way to view their classes, dining hours, shuttle schedules, map of the campus, and more. In a similar way, Bren students’ busy daily lives would be improved if there was a mobile app that combines all ICS school information. This application would give students the opportunity to become more aware of events, have easier access to counselor schedules, and view important major and course descriptions on the go. This Android application would even be a mechanism to further establish closer community of aware and involved ICS students. Since this application would also be available to UCI students in other schools, this application would aid other students who are potentially thinking about switching majors by providing them with important major information. Overall, J-Unit hopes that this Bren ICS School Android Application will help UCI students as well as potentially raise overall campus awareness of the school and the exciting events/courses it has to offer.

2.0 Business Objective (Victor) 
J-Unit business objectives include improved academic awareness, information organization/mobility, and visibility within the ICS school for students.  This mobile application intends to increase academic awareness by providing convenient event updates and ICS student affairs office timings.  Course curriculum information and descriptions, quarterly schedules, and degree information will be organized in distinct page options.  Having to jump around between difficult to find requirements pages, degree course listings, and quarterly pages will be as minimized as possible.  The application as a whole will support the business objective of visibility within the ICS school as it will provide students with an easier way to access all necessary information pertaining to the school. Andrew’s Notes: This mobile app is intended for students of the ICS school to provide easily accessible information about the school to learn and also plan effectively.

Victor’s Notes: We want to make ICS website more streamlined, more efficient, accessible to present curriculum in more organized manner.

3.0 Current Situation and Problem/ Opportunity Statement (Andrew)
Currently the website for the Donald Bren School of Information and Computer Sciences is made for use by all kinds of visitors to the site, including faculty, graduate and undergraduate students, prospective students, alumni and all other visitors interested in the content on this website. This website includes a substantial amount of information, such as school-wide events, research opportunities, major and minor curriculums, faculty descriptions, and other information that pertains to the ICS school. The website is sufficient in that it contains enough information for visitors to the site, but as of now, there is an opportunity to develop a mobile application based on this website that caters specifically to undergraduate students. Retrieving information, such as major curriculums and class descriptions, is difficult to achieve on the website, as it is currently designed for all visitors. This mobile application would include information relevant only to the undergraduate student community in the ICS school, making information retrieval from the website significantly more efficient. Having a centralized, organized source of information about undergraduate activities would be helpful, as the current website viewed on phones is not user-friendly. With the option of developing a mobile application, this opportunity is optimal.

Andrew’s Notes: Currently, the website for the ICS school is not easily navigated and does not cater to undergraduate students who may want to use alternative methods of getting information from the website otherwise.

Victor’s Notes:  There is no mobile application for ICS website, and no centralized, well organized application that helps students.

4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints (Victor)
This mobile application will be supported by Android devices only, which is assumed to be the choice of mobile device by a significant portion of UCI students.  Access to content must be available to students at all times, and must be consistent with the information that is on the actual ICS website.  Students will have a need to use this application because the current website is unsatisfactory in helping their needs efficiently.  The application will be able to effectively inherit and implement features from the website that students find useful, and leave out the features that are not useful.  Furthermore, this application will not leave out pertinent features that are implemented by the website which would increase the usefulness of the application.

6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements (Andrew)
The main features for the ICS School mobile application includes the following:

Access to information on undergraduate course listings and course descriptions. Users must be able to navigate through categorized lists for classes, organized by major. Course listings must be listed for the current school year and updated accordingly. Users must also be able to read information for courses as currently described in the ICS website.
Access to information on school-wide events. Users must be able to navigate through events related to undergraduate students in the ICS school. The events must be listed for the current school year and updated accordingly.
Access to counselor contact information. Users must be able to look up times and availability of their counselors. Availability and contact information of the counselors must be listed for the current school year.
A native user interface, which allows any users that have experience with the phone to easily use this application.
Future integration with the widely-used mobile application for University of California, Irvine: ZotMobile. This app does not include any features specific to the school of ICS, but potentiall can if integrated with this ICS school app.

9.0 Potential Risks (Victor)
Potential risks include a lack of interest from students, and others.  They may prefer to address their ICS academic information through only the website and not on a mobile platform because of advantageous qualities of computers versus mobile devices: screen size, printing, easier typing, etc.  The type of technology must also be compatible with both the creators and users.  Possessing familiarity with Android development, as well as the ability to quickly learn new skills and requirements, will be key in completing the application with all of the originally intended features intact.  Users must also have a preference or capability of using android devices and its applications.  Mac iOS platforms are preferred by some students; Mac laptops are preferred by some students over PC laptops.

Certain features that are effective on the website could be difficult or not possible to transfer over to the application.

In case the fully functional demo breaks, we have the second product ready to demo, but only presenting selected functions).

4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints (Victor)
The ICS Schools Android Application mock-up must be completed by March 15th, 2013, in order to present to the Informatics 151 class. The development and implementation of this mobile application should be actively supported by the ICS school and the community of ICS undergraduate students. In order to measure the success of this application, it must have at least 300 downloads within a year’s time. The application will be able to effectively inherit and implement features from the website that students find useful, and leave out the features that are not useful.  Furthermore, this application will not leave out pertinent features that are implemented by the website which contribute to the website’s positive aspects and would increase the usefulness of the application.  

Project team members must work together to address weaknesses in the website and research skills and technologies necessary to build the application so that it can overcome these weaknesses.  Having the capability to transfer the core essence of what the website provides is also critical.  If project members lack the skills necessary to build a certain portion of the application, then they are aware of helpful sources to approach in order to address that certain need.

5.0 Analysis of Option and Recommendation (Saloni)
	In order to make sure that creating this application is the best solution to the current problem, J-Unit has assessed the following options: 
1) Do nothing and leave the ICS website the way it is currently is. 
2) Make a mobile-friendly version of the site.
3) Create a separate mobile application for ICS students. 

The members of J-Unit have assessed that Option 3 is the best solution to handle the current problem the ICS website poses today. Option 1 was decided against because it does not align with the overarching goal of improvement that J-Unit was founded upon. By leaving the site as-is, undergraduate students’ lives wouldn’t be any easier and accessing important information wouldn’t be any more efficient. Even though there currently is a way to access the ICS website online from a mobile device, it is difficult to navigate and find important information an undergraduate student would want to access on the go. Option 2 would be a feasible solution to the problem of the non mobile-friendly ICS website. However, it would not address the problem that undergraduate students currently face in trying to find information specifically directed towards them. Undergraduate students would still have to sift through the mobile website in order to find the information that they need. Option 3 is the best solution because it is user-friendly, mobile, and will cater to undergraduate students. The mobile application will give developers the option of constantly improving upon it, making it more user-friendly and fun for students to use.
